AWS 1/8 

AWS regions = a geographical area where there is cluster of data centres (independent)

- Multiple physical buildings within a region - ensure high availability + redundancy 
- Ensuring a region is close to customers 
- Aws services are region scoped - local laws 
- Each aws region has it’s own unique identifier - i.e “us-east-1” , “eu-west-1”

*AWS regions have a min 3 and max 3*
- AWS region (Europe) eu west 2 
- AWS availability zone = eu west 2a , eu west 2b , eu west 2c


How to choose an AWS Region ?

- Latency + proximity = closer region to users to user for faster performance + reduced latency  
- Available services within a region = this is because not all regions provide the service you need 
- Costs = costs can vary between regions 
- Compliance with data regulation + legal requirements 


AWS Availability zones = Multiple isolated locations within a region - I.e separate data centres in the same area 
- Isolation key for maintaining high availability + isloated from disaster 
- Redundant power , network and etc 
- They’re connected with high bandwidth 


Points of presence (edge locations)
- Aws local outposts/sites across the world = they have 400
- Edge locations = another name of points of presence and help deliver content closer to your user 

*they cache and serve up data from a closer point so users get fast loading time + lower latency*
*edge location -> closer to user = faster speed 


